PSEUDOCODE
==========

Configure SysTick:
    Load RELOAD register with (SystemCoreClock / 1000 - 1) -> 1ms tick
    Clear current value register
    Enable SysTick with processor clock source
    Enable SysTick interrupt

Global ms_counter increments every SysTick interrupt (every 1ms)

delay_ms(n):
    Record current ms_counter value
    Wait until ms_counter has advanced by n

Main:
    Setup PA5 as output (LED)
    Loop forever:
        Toggle LED
        delay_ms(500)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA5   =>  Onboard LED (LD4) - Active HIGH

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY REGISTERS
=============

SysTick (System Timer)
`SysTick` lives in the ARM Cortex-M core itself, not STM32 peripherals.

|-----------|-----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register  | Field           | Description                                                                      |
|-----------|-----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| STK->CTRL | bit0  Enable    | Enables the SysTick counter                                                      |
| STK->CTRL | bit1  TICKINT   | When set, triggers SysTick_Handler every time counter reaches 0                  |
| STK->CTRL | bit2  CLKSOURCE | 1 = use processor clock (HCLK). 0 = use HCLK/8. We use 1                         |
| STK->CTRL | bit16 COUNTFLAG | Reads 1 if counter hit 0 since last read. Cleared on read                        |
| STK->LOAD | bits[23:0]      | Reload value. Counter counts down from this to 0, then reloads. Max 24-bit value |
| STK->VAL  | bits[23:0]      | Current counter value. Writing any value clears it to 0                          |
|-----------|-----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* Off-by-one in LOAD value, The counter counts from LOAD down to 0, which is
  LOAD + 1 clock cycles. So for exactly 1ms at 16MHz we need 15999, not
  16000. The formula (SYSCLK / 1000) - 1 handles this correctly. Getting this
  wrong makes every delay slightly off, which compounds over time.

* ms_ticks must be volatile, the compiler sees that ms_ticks is never written
  inside delay_ms() and will happily optimize the while loop into an infinite
  loop or eliminate it entirely if volatile is missing. This is one of the most
  classic bare-metal bugs.

* Subtraction trick in delay_ms, Using (ms_ticks - start) < ms instead of
  ms_ticks < (start + ms) correctly handles the case where ms_ticks wraps around
  at 0xFFFFFFFF back to 0 (happens after ~49 days of uptime). The subtraction
  version is rollover-safe.

* SysTick LOAD is only 24-bit, Maximum reload value is 0xFFFFFF = 16,777,215. At
  16MHz, that gives a max single tick period of about 1.048 seconds. We cannot
  set a 2-second single tick. Use a counter (like ms_ticks) for longer
  durations.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* SysTick is core, not vendor, Unlike TIM2 or USART2, SysTick is part of the ARM
  Cortex-M0+ core specification. Its registers, behavior, and ISR name
  (SysTick_Handler) are identical across all Cortex-M chips from all
  vendors. This code would run on an STM32F4 with zero changes to the SysTick
  part.

* This becomes our system timebase, from now onwards, delay_ms() replaces the
  crude loop counter. Every future program that needs time will build on top of
  ms_ticks. And after some programs later, we'll use ms_ticks for non-blocking
  timing patterns like if ((ms_ticks - last_toggle) >= interval) which lets the
  CPU do multiple things at once without blocking in a while.

* Polling inside delay_ms still blocks, The CPU sits inside the while loop doing
  nothing useful. It's accurate, but not efficient. WWDG and Low Power Programs
  will show later how to sleep the CPU during waits and wake only on the SysTick
  interrupt, saving power significantly.

